# Skill Generator

Generates a complete, spec-compliant, enterprise-grade OpenCode skill from a folder of internal documentation files.

## When You Are Invoked

The user will provide one of:
- A path to a folder containing one or more `.md` files
- Pasted content of documentation files
- A mix of both

Your job: produce a ready-to-install skill folder. Do not ask for lengthy clarification upfront. Read the docs, make smart decisions, present the result. Ask only if something is genuinely ambiguous and cannot be inferred.

---

## Step 1 — Inventory the Source Docs

If given a folder path, list its contents then read each `.md` file. For each file, identify:
- **Domain**: what topic does it cover? (e.g. unit testing, Kafka naming, exception handling)
- **Nature**: prescriptive (rules/standards) vs descriptive (explanations/background)
- **Size**: approximate line count

Then decide: **one skill or multiple skills?**

| Condition | Decision |
|---|---|
| All files share the same agent trigger context | One skill |
| Files cover clearly distinct concerns a dev would invoke separately | Multiple skills |
| One file is very large (>300 lines) and self-contained | One skill + reference file |

**Announce your decision before writing.** Example:
> "I'll generate two skills: `java-testing` covering unit and integration tests, and `kafka-conventions` covering naming and configuration. Proceeding."

---

## Step 2 — Distil the Content

For each skill, extract signal from the source docs:

### What to keep
- Hard rules: MUST / MUST NOT / always / never
- Naming conventions with concrete examples
- Structural patterns (class layout, package structure, annotation order)
- Anti-patterns and what to avoid
- Short, high-signal code examples (< 20 lines)

### What to discard
- Background explanations that don't constrain agent behaviour
- Historical context or rationale ("why we chose X")
- Repetition across files — consolidate
- Anything the agent can infer from context

### Section structure for SKILL.md body

```
## Rules
Numbered list. Imperative mood. One rule per item. Actionable.

## Naming Conventions
Tables preferred. Pattern + Example columns.

## Structure & Patterns
How to organise code, files, packages. Short examples where useful.

## Anti-Patterns
What NOT to do. One line per anti-pattern.

## Examples
Only if they materially help. Keep under 20 lines per example.
```

Omit any section that would be empty.

---

## Step 3 — Write the Frontmatter

### `name` field
- Lowercase alphanumeric + single hyphens only
- Must match the folder name exactly
- 1–64 characters
- Regex: `^[a-z0-9]+(-[a-z0-9]+)*$`
- Examples: `java-testing`, `kafka-conventions`, `exception-handling`, `angular-standards`

### `description` field
- Maximum 1024 characters
- **This is the primary trigger mechanism** — the agent reads ONLY name + description to decide whether to load this skill
- Must convey: what the skill enforces + when to activate
- Use strong signal words: MUST, CRITICAL, always activate when...
- Include synonyms and natural-language phrases a developer would say
- Template:

```
CRITICAL: Enforces [team] standards for [domain]. MUST activate when writing, reviewing,
or generating [artifacts]. Covers: [A], [B], [C]. Always use when the user mentions
[trigger words or phrases].
```

> ⚠️ Agents tend to undertrigger. Be explicit and direct in the description.
> Words like MUST and CRITICAL consistently improve trigger reliability.

---

## Step 4 — Decide on `references/`

Move content to `references/` when:
- A source doc is large (> 200 lines) and covers a specific sub-topic
- The agent only needs full detail occasionally, not on every invocation
- The SKILL.md body would exceed 500 lines without offloading

For each reference file:
- Keep it focused on one sub-topic
- Add a table of contents at the top if > 300 lines
- Point to it clearly from SKILL.md body:

```markdown
> For full naming convention tables, read `references/naming.md`.
> Load `references/kafka-config.md` when configuring consumers or producers.
```

---

## Step 5 — Output the Skill

Create the full folder structure:

```
<skill-name>/
├── SKILL.md
└── references/        ← only if needed
    └── <topic>.md
```

Default output location: `.opencode/skills/<skill-name>/`
Use user-specified path if provided.

Present to the user:
1. Full content of `SKILL.md`
2. List of reference files created with a one-line description of each
3. The installation note below

---

## Installation Note — Always Present This

```
Global install (available in all projects):
  cp -r <skill-name>/ ~/.config/opencode/skills/

Project install (this repo only):
  cp -r <skill-name>/ .opencode/skills/

Restart OpenCode after installing to pick up the new skill.
```

---

## Quality Checklist — Run Before Presenting Output

- [ ] `name` matches folder name and passes regex `^[a-z0-9]+(-[a-z0-9]+)*$`
- [ ] `description` is under 1024 characters
- [ ] `description` contains MUST / CRITICAL and clear trigger phrases
- [ ] `description` lists the main domains/topics covered
- [ ] SKILL.md body is under 500 lines
- [ ] All rules are imperative and actionable — no explanatory prose in rules sections
- [ ] No section is present but empty
- [ ] No wall-of-text copy-pasted verbatim from source docs
- [ ] Large source docs (> 200 lines) moved to `references/` and referenced from SKILL.md
- [ ] Reference files have clear load instructions in SKILL.md
- [ ] Code examples are under 20 lines and genuinely high-signal

Fix any failing item before presenting output.

---

## Edge Cases

**Conflicting rules across files**: Apply the most restrictive rule. Add a comment noting the conflict at the top of the relevant section.

**Very large source folder (10+ files)**: Group by domain, one skill per group. Present the grouping plan to the user before writing anything.

**Source doc is already a SKILL.md**: Treat as a draft — apply the quality checklist and rewrite the description for better triggering.

**Non-English source docs**: Generate the skill in the same language as the docs unless the user requests otherwise.

---

## Hard Constraints

- **NEVER modify the content of source documentation files** — they are read-only inputs. When placing a doc in `references/`, copy it verbatim. The only writing you do is `SKILL.md` and new reference files derived from the source docs.
- Never copy-paste entire source documents into SKILL.md body
- Never write vague descriptions like "covers coding standards"
- Never include prose that explains rather than constrains agent behaviour
- Never create `references/` if all content fits cleanly under 500 lines
- Never ask for permission before reading files — read them
- Never present output without completing the quality checklist
